---
By: Henri F. Amiel
Locus:
  Page: 264
  Verse: 5
Tags:
  - Illusions
---
The philosopher laughs, for he alone escapes being duped, while he sees
other men the victims of persistent illusion. He is like some mischievous
spectator of a ball who has cleverly taken all the strings from the
violins, and yet sees musicians and dancers moving and pirouetting before
him as though the music were still playing.
